"HD5131"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_blurb":"Judge, US District Court for the District of Connecticut","notable_category":["law"],"primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_A._Ingersoll","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"birth":{"year":1798,"month":10,"day":19,"city":"New Haven","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1860,"month":1,"day":12,"city":"New Haven","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States","age":61},"residence":{},"burial":{"plot_notes":"Grove Street Cemetery, New Haven CT"},"baptism":{},"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"law","header":"US federal judge nominated by President Pierce","body":"Charles Anthony Ingersoll served as a United States federal judge, nominated to the bench by President Franklin Pierce in the 1850s. The appointment placed him on the Connecticut federal bench during the politically charged decade leading into the Civil War. He continued the Ingersoll family's principal role in Connecticut legal and judicial life — his father Jonathan Jr. having served as Superior Court Judge and Lieutenant Governor, his elder brother Ralph in Congress and as US Minister to Russia."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Father of two sons who continued legal tradition","body":"Charles Anthony's two sons Charles Dennis Ingersoll (1843-1905, New York City lawyer) and Thomas Chester Ingersoll (1845-1884) continued the family legal tradition. The Ingersoll name extended across three generations of the New York and Philadelphia bars in addition to the original Connecticut branch. His brother Charles Jared Ingersoll (the Philadelphia cousin) had been the family progenitor of the Pennsylvania legal line."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Born 1798, died 1860 age sixty-two","body":"Charles Anthony Ingersoll was born in 1798 — likely a twin to his sister Harriet Ingersoll Voorhees who shares the same birth year. He died in 1860 at age sixty-two on the eve of the Civil War. His father Jonathan Ingersoll Jr. had been Lieutenant Governor of Connecticut at the time of his birth and continued in that role until his death in 1823."}],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","role":"student","notes":"Yale University AM 1827"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"education":[],"career":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Charles Anthony Ingersoll","first_name":"Charles","last_name":"Ingersoll","middle_name":"Anthony","married_names":[],"gender":"male","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1779824780/judgecharlesingersoll_ydejnz.jpg"},"slug":"charles-ingersoll-1798"},"HD5129":{"id":"HD5129","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker_bool":true},"parents":{"father_id":"HD5112","mother_id":"I01302"},"tags":["judge","lawyer"],"research_tags":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I01303","date_year":1885,"date_month":6,"date_day":2,"location_city":"Manhattan","location_state":"New York","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1905,"children_ids":["HD5132","HD5133","HD5134"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"birth":{"year":1843,"month":1,"day":15,"city":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1905,"month":1,"day":8,"city":"Manhattan","state":"New York","country":"United States","age":61},"residence":{},"burial":{"plot_notes":"Green-Wood Cemetery, Greenwood Heights Brooklyn NY"},"baptism":{},"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"NYC judge continuing Ingersoll legal tradition","body":"Charles Dennis Ingersoll continued the Ingersoll family legal tradition across the New York and Connecticut bars — making him the fourth consecutive generation of Ingersoll lawyers and judges descending from Rev. Jonathan Ingersoll. His grandfather Jonathan Ingersoll Jr. was Lieutenant Governor of Connecticut; his father Charles Anthony Ingersoll was a US federal judge; his uncle Ralph Isaacs Ingersoll was a US Congressman and Minister to Russia; his cousin Charles Roberts Ingersoll became Governor of Connecticut. The Ingersoll legal dynasty spanned 1747-1905 (Rev. Jonathan to Charles Dennis) across five generations."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Married widow Katharine Sanders Varnum, 1885","body":"Charles Dennis married Katharine Corse Sanders Varnum on June 2, 1885 in Manhattan New York — she had previously been married to Robert Taylor Varnum. The couple had three children together: Hamilton Ingersoll (1888-1940), Anita Ingersoll Gwynne (1891-1970), and Justine Ingersoll Arnold (1893-1984). His grandchildren through these three children form the documented twentieth-century Ingersoll-Arnold-Gwynne descendants of the original Connecticut bar family."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"New Haven 1843 to Manhattan 1905, Green-Wood Cemetery","body":"Charles Dennis Ingersoll was born January 15, 1843 in New Haven Connecticut and died January 8, 1905 in Manhattan New York at age sixty-one. He is buried at Green-Wood Cemetery in Greenwood Heights Brooklyn New York — breaking the Ingersoll family Grove Street Cemetery tradition through his NYC career. His wife Katharine died in Menton France in 1922."}],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"education":[],"career":[],"bio":{"display_name":"J